observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to recognize all lands owned by the Municipality in the books;
Direct the Municipal Assessor to expedite the titling of the lands of the Municipality;
Direct the General Services Officer to conduct a complete physical inventory of all PPE and prepare the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment;
Conduct the disposal procedure for the unserviceable PPE and derecognize the same from the books; and
Prepare adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance of the CIP and disclose the CIP balance that cannot be traceable.

We reiterated that Management require the:
Coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the GSO towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in recording of supplies and materials; and establishment of sufficient stock room for proper storage of items of inventories;
GSO-designate/Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a complete Report on the Physical Count of Inventories on a semestral basis in order to determine the correctness of the recorded inventories in the books of accounts of the Municipality and to ensure that semestral count of Inventory items is promptly conducted and the corresponding report is submitted on time to the Audit Team;
Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain supplies ledger cards (SLC) and stock cards (SC), respectively, for each type of inventories and reconcile the accounting and property records periodically to bring these accounts into agreement; and
MGSO to prepare and maintain Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for each item of inventory with shelf life of more than one year to establish proper accountability of accountable officers concerned.

We recommended that Management direct Municipal Accountant to:
Cause the thorough review of the Due to BIR account and the religious preparation and maintenance of an appropriate Subsidiary Ledger for each account;
Submit the Schedule of Due to BIR and ensure to prepare and submit this to the Office of the Auditor;
Establish a system or routine that will be observed by accounting personnel in maintaining the subsidiary ledger and schedule of Payables to ensure that adequate information is captured in those records.

We recommended the Management to:
Settle the unpaid Capital Gains Tax (CGT) and Documentary Stamp Tax (DST) for the titled lots and facilitate the transfer of the title in the name of the Municipality;
Charge any penalties and interest incurred due to the late filing and payment of CGT and DST, if applicable, to the responsible official;
Immediately secure the Lot Status Certificate and Alienable and Disposable Certificate for all untitled lots from the DENR prior to further action or utilization;
Promptly initiate the titling process for the untitled lots; and
Retrospectively secure the necessary indemnity agreements/bond or explore legal remedies to protect the Municipality's interests.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the HRMO to submit to the Audit Team the memorandum signed by the Municipal Mayor approving the salary increase;
HRMO to explain the inconsistencies or provide update in the role assignment on identified JO workers;
Require the HRMO to ensure formal documentation of any rate changes through signed contract amendments before processing payroll adjustments, and to submit these to the Audit Team promptly as the situation arises; and
Direct MACCO to conduct monthly reconciliation between contract terms and payroll records to ensure that the rate being paid aligns with the rate stated in the signed contract.

We recommended that Management:
Submit to the Audit Team the remaining employment contracts for 49 COS workers;
Prepare an Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern Plan, and formulate policies and guidelines so that the necessity and propriety of hiring job order employees are justified;
Review, along with the department heads, the current manpower matrix to ensure that the hiring and engagement of job orders are in accordance with the needs of the Municipality;
Provide the Office of the Auditor with a Certification by the Local Chief Executive/Personnel Officer that the activities/ services to be rendered by the COS and JO workers cannot be provided by regular or permanent personnel of the LGU; and
Require the Accounting Office and the Human Resource Management Office to ensure that required supporting documents for claims particularly for first claims of the JO workers are attached to the payroll.

We recommended the Management to:
require the GSO to reflect in the RPCPPE the actual PPE counted and reconciliation between the records of the MA and GSO be undertaken and effect the necessary adjustments in the accounting books to fairly present the said accounts in the financial statements;
perform One-Time Cleansing of PPE as prescribed in COA Circular 2020-006 to be able to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
require the GSO to maintain the pertinent reports and property records of Road Networks to be able to provide reliable basis on the amounts presented in the financial statements;
require Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to FS the road network system;
dispose the unserviceable properties and the corresponding cost or value be dropped from the books of accounts;
direct the Municipal Accountant to identify possible items that need to be excluded from the PPE account and make proper adjustments if deemed necessary;
ensure that an ICS is on file or had been prepared by the GSO before these semi-expendable assets are removed from PPE account to ensure control and accountability; and
direct the Municipal Assessor and officials concerned to prioritize the transfer of ownership over parcels of land without TCT/OCT to the LGU to avoid exposing the same to possible third-party claims and land disputes.

We recommended that Management require the:
Municipal Treasurer to prepare yearly a duly certified list of taxpayers based on the updated RPTARs showing the names of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year, and furnish the same to the Municipal Accounting Office at the beginning of every fiscal year;
Municipal Accountant to record RPT/SET Receivable yearly based on the duly certified list provided by the MTO;
Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the JEVs and the Abstract of RPT Collections in accordance with the provisions of GAAM and Manual on the NGAS for LGUs; and
Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records in order to come up with accurate and reliable reports on the levy of RPT and SET.

We recommended that Management:
require the concerned officers and employees to immediately settle/liquidate their outstanding cash advances through the submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports, otherwise, enforce the withholding of salary, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002;
stop the grant of additional cash advances to all personnel with unliquidated cash advances until such time previous cash advances are fully settled, and see to it that officials and employees who seek transfer to other offices or those filing for terminal leaves are not given certificates of clearance until their balances are paid;
request for the write-off of dormant accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005, if applicable;
prepare and maintain complete and updated SLs, ageing and other subsidiary records of the accounts presented in the FS in accordance with Section 10 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume II; and
monitor and establish controls to ensure the timely liquidation of cash advances through updated monthly ageing of the same to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and ensure that the rules and regulations on the grant of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that Management require the:
coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the GSO towards the full implementation of the perpetual inventory method in recording of supplies and materials; and establishment of sufficient stock room for proper storage of items of inventories;
GSO-designate/Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a complete Report on the Physical Count of Inventories semestrally in order to determine the correctness of the recorded inventories in the books of accounts of the Municipality and to ensure that semestral count of Inventory items is promptly conducted and the corresponding report is submitted on time to the Audit Team;
Municipal Accountant and GSO to maintain supplies ledger cards (SLC) and stock cards (SC), respectively, for each type of inventories and reconcile the accounting and property records periodically to bring these accounts into agreement; and
MGSO to prepare and maintain Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) for each item of inventory with shelf life of more than one year to establish proper accountability of accountable officers concerned.

We recommended that management:
Ensure that the LCE’s authority to hire and engage JO workers are within the ambit of good governance, administrative necessity and fiscal adequacy of the LGU;
Formulate uniform policy and procedures in engaging and managing JO workers taking into consideration the existing law, rules and regulations;
Conduct personnel audit, review, assessment and evaluation of the existing manpower complement of the LGU so as to determine the necessity and propriety of engaging JO workers;
Use appropriate forms of contract stipulating the duties and responsibilities of the JO, the expected output and deliverables and the standard wage rates; and
Strictly comply with the documentary requirements in COA Circular      2012-001.

We recommended that Management:

send demand letters to the concerned Accountable Officers (AOs) requesting immediate liquidation of the cash advance or settlement of the amounts due from them;

suspend the salaries of erring accountable officers until such time that full settlement of their cash advances are effected;

immediately stop the grant of additional cash advances to all officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances until such time that previous cash advances are fully settled; and

ensure that rules and regulations on the grant and liquidation of cash advances are strictly observed.

We recommended that Management:

re-establish and reinforce the deputation of barangay officials to aid the Municipality in collecting taxes by setting their specific functions and responsibilities;

create new positions and provide more additional capable personnel that will cause the issuance of NOD and the monitoring of the delinquent tax payers;

intensify the tax campaign by sending treasury personnel to barangay especially during barangay assemblies for tax information drive in order to invite more taxpayers to pay taxes on time; and

instruct the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to update the RPTARs and submit a duly certified list to the Municipal Accounting Office, showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year; and

instruct the Municipal Accounting Office to adjust the receivables recorded at the beginning of the year based on the certified list of taxpayers.

We recommended that Management:

secure copies of the Torrens Titles of its lots drawn in the name of the Municipality from the Land Registration Authority to eliminate the risk that the municipality may be evicted from the lot they are presently occupying if ownership cannot be established;

in coordination with concerned officials, prepare and maintain the complete list of lots owned by the municipality with details as to description, area and value;

ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Land Titles for judicious endorsement to their successor; and

recognize all the properties of the municipality in the books whether these are acquired through purchase, donation or any other mode of acquisition.
